Data analysis

Source: vignettes/analysis.Rmd
analysis.Rmd
library(rGeoCBI)
library(ruODK)
library(magrittr)
library(leaflet)
library(reactable)

This vignette will provide a worked example of accessing and downloading the burn grading submissions, and calculating the GeoCBI from the raw data.

Request an ODK Central account

Request an ODK Central account here. You will receive a registration email. Your username will be your email address, you can choose your own password. With those credentials, you have read access to ODK Central, the place where burn grading submissions are uploaded to.

This step is required only once for every data analyst.

Setup ruODK

For details, refer to ruODK vignette “setup”.

Set default credentials and settings to simplify work with ruODK later. Credentials live as environment variables in your .Renviron file. Changes to .Renviron require a restart of the R session.

usethis::edit_r_environ()

# Paste with your credentials
ODKC_URL="https://odkcentral.dbca.wa.gov.au"
ODKC_UN="YOUR_EMAIL"
ODKC_PW="YOUR_PASSWORD"
ODKC_PID=27
ODKC_FID="build_Burn-Grading-0-1_1578487677"

# Save .Renviron and restart your R session.

Since we’ll only work with one form and have set the neccessary settings as defaults, ruODK will default to our form without any further ado.

If you need to navigate between forms, you can setup ruODK with the respective OData service URL:

# ODK Central's OData URL contains base URL, project ID, and form ID
# ODK Central credentials can live in .Renviron, see vignette "setup"
ruODK::ru_setup(
  svc = paste0("https://odkcentral.dbca.wa.gov.au/v1/projects/27/",
               "forms/build_Burn-Grading-0-1_1578487677.svc"),
  un = Sys.getenv("ODKC_UN"),
  pw = Sys.getenv("ODKC_PW")
)
#> <ruODK settings>
#>   Default ODK Central Project ID:  27 
#>   Default ODK Central Form ID:  build_Burn-Grading-0-1_1578487677 
#>   Default ODK Central URL:  https://odkcentral.dbca.wa.gov.au 
#>   Default ODK Central Username:  florian.mayer@dbca.wa.gov.au 
#>   Default ODK Central Password: run ruODK::get_default_pw() to show

Download data

For an overview on accessing data from ODK Central, read the ODK Central docs.

For a background on accessing data from R, refer to ruODK vignette “odata-api”.

In a pinch, we can always download a ZIP archive of all submissions and all photos from ODK Central.

Here, we’ll use ruODK to download submissions from ODK Central.

burngrading01 <- ruODK::odata_submission_get(
  verbose = T, 
  tz = "Australia/Perth", 
  local_dir = fs::path("media"), 
  wkt=T
)

Calculate GeoCBI

Parse raw data into numeric scale values, apply GeoCBI formula.

Values are coded as <grade>_<url-safe-label>, where grade are numbers 0.0, 0.5, 1.0, 1.5 through to 3.0, and the labels are intelligible but url-safe variable names. Fraction of coverages (fcov) also are prefixed with their grade, which ranges from 0.0 to 1.0 in increments of 0.25.

bg_geocbi <- add_geocbi(burngrading01)

Visualise

The data shown here are test data (not real burn gradings) and come from the real form.

Map

leaflet::leaflet(width = 800, height = 600) %>%
    leaflet::addProviderTiles("Esri.WorldImagery", group = "Aerial") %>%
    leaflet::addProviderTiles("OpenStreetMap.Mapnik", group = "Place names") %>%
    leaflet::clearBounds() %>%
    # leaflet::setView(130,-33, 4) %>% 
    leaflet::addAwesomeMarkers(
        data = bg_geocbi,
        lng = ~location_longitude, lat = ~location_latitude,
        icon = leaflet::makeAwesomeIcon(text = ~geocbi, markerColor = "red"),
        label = ~ glue::glue("[{geocbi}] {plot_name} {observation_start_time}"),
        popup = ~ glue::glue(
          "<h3>{plot_name} - GeoCBI {geocbi}</h3>",
          "Survey start {observation_start_time}</br>",
          "Reporter {reporter}</br>",
          "Device {device_id}</br>",
          
          "<h5>Plot</h5>",
          "<div>Burn homogeneous throughout plot: ",
          "{homogeneous_burn_severity}</div>",
          '<img src="{plot_photo}" height="150px" alt="Plot photo"></img>',
          
          "<h5>Lower strata 1-3</h5>",
          "<div>Stratum 2: Dom veg {s2_dominant_vegetation}</div>",
          "<div>Stratum 3: Dom veg {s3_dominant_vegetation}</div>",
          "<div>Stratum 4: Dom veg {s4_dominant_vegetation}</div>",
          "<div>Stratum 5: Dom veg {s5_dominant_vegetation}</div>",
          '<img src="{s1_photo}" height="150px" alt="Stratum 1 photo"></img>',

Table

Each row expands to show details. Here, we show all linked photos.

bg_geocbi %>% reactable::reactable(
  sortable = T, 
  filterable = T,
  details = function(index) {
    htmltools::tags$div(
      htmltools::tags$img(width="200px;", alt="Plot photo", src=bg_geocbi[index,]$plot_photo),
      htmltools::tags$img(width="200px;", alt="Stratum 1 photo", src=bg_geocbi[index,]$s1_photo),
      htmltools::tags$img(width="200px;", alt="Stratum 1 photo", src=bg_geocbi[index,]$s2_photo),
      htmltools::tags$img(width="200px;", alt="Stratum 1 photo", src=bg_geocbi[index,]$s3_photo),
      htmltools::tags$img(width="200px;", alt="Stratum 1 photo", src=bg_geocbi[index,]$s4_photo),
      htmltools::tags$img(width="200px;", alt="Stratum 1 photo", src=bg_geocbi[index,]$s5_photo)
    )})
